{"title_page": "A Taste of Blackberries", "text_new": "{{Infobox book \n| name     = A Taste of Blackberries\n| title_orig  = \n| image     = File:A Taste of Blackberries library binding.jpg\n| caption = First edition\n| author    = [[Doris Buchanan Smith]]\n| illustrator  = Charles Robinson\n| cover_artist = \n| country    = United States\n| language   = English\n| series    = \n| genre     = [[Children's fiction|Children's novel]] \n| publisher   = [[Thomas Y. Crowell Co.]] (now [[HarperCollins]])\n| release_date = May 1973\n| media_type  = Print\n| pages     = 85 (paperback)\n| awards       = [[ALA Notable Children's Book]], Georgia Children's Author of the Year, Georgia Children's Book Award, Georgia Author of the Year, [[Josette Frank Award]], [[List of literary awards|Zilveren Griffel]]\n| isbn     = 9780064402385\n| congress   = \n| oclc     = \n| preceded_by  = \n| followed_by  = \n}}\n'''''A Taste of Blackberries''''' ([[HarperCollins]], 1973) is an award-winning children's book by [[Doris Buchanan Smith]] (June 1, 1934 - August 8, 2002).<ref>{{cite news|last=Derrick|first=Henry|title=Obituaries: Hayesville, NC: Doris Buchanan Smith, 68, Wrote for Adolescents|pages=P.C6|url=http://find.galegroup.com/gps/infomark.do?&contentSet=IAC-Documents&type=retrieve&tabID=T004&prodId=IPS&docId=CJ121436858&source=gale&srcprod=ITOF&userGroupName=nypl&version=1.0|accessdate=19 April 2011|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=14 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&disableHighlighting=false&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1663000396&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=3ce48fd1879e2c4e7ba70c5f5862ea9a|work=St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers|publisher=Gale Biography In Context|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Background and reception==\nWhen [[Doris Buchanan Smith|Doris Smith]] set out to find a publisher for ''A Taste of Blackberries'' what she found instead was rejection.  Editors believed her story was better suited to adults than to children.  In the end however the main theme is what set it apart from other books for children and earned critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scherer|first=Sally|title=Author of Children\u2019s Books Found Success by Breaking Rules|newspaper=The Macon Telegraph|date=18 April 1996}}</ref>  If death had at one time been a common theme in books for children, think ''[[Oliver Twist]]'', it had long since become taboo.  In 1952, [[E. B. White]] reintroduced the theme to young readers in his classic ''[[Charlotte's Web]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Lois Rauch Gibson|author2=Laura M. Zaidman|title=Death in Children's Literature: Taboo or Not Taboo?|journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly|date=Winter 1991|volume=16| issue = 4|pages=232\u2013234|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/childrens_literature_association_quarterly/summary/v016/16.4.gibson.html|accessdate=30 August 2012|doi=10.1353/chq.0.0855}}</ref>\n\nFor many years ''[[Charlotte's Web]]'' was the accepted template for addressing mortality in children's books.  Then Smith's story appeared, a story in which animals do not stand-in for humans.  In the 1970s, [[literary realism]] had taken hold, and Smith was at the vanguard of the movement,<ref>{{cite news|last=Habich|first=John|title=She tells kids the bitter and the sweet|newspaper=Tallahassee Democrat|date=December 1980}}</ref> acquainting young readers with \"the darker, harsher side of life.\"  According to author and blogger Pauline Dewan; \"Many writers believe that authors do not help children by sheltering them from the problems of the real world.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dewan|first=Pauline|title=Children\u2019s Literary Classics: The Realistic Genre|url=http://childliterature.net/childlit/realistic/index.html|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref>  Indeed, according to the author, many young readers told her \"they liked it because it was sad.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Jingle|title=A Realist in Children's Books|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal|date=December 10, 1978}}</ref>  Interviewed for the ''[[Dictionary of Literary Biography]]'', Smith recalled that ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was supposed to have been an adventure, but when an unexpected plot twist occurred to her Smith locked the manuscript in a drawer and forget about it.  Only later did she resume by focusing on the differences in the way that children and adults respond to mortality, while writing from the point of view of the child.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Keenan|first=Hugh T.|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|journal=Dictionary of Literary Biography|year=1981|volume=52|page=353}}</ref>\n\nRejected by as many as three publishers, ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was ultimately accepted by [[Thomas Y. Crowell Co.]], now [[HarperCollins]], and released to wide acclaim in May 1973.  \"Smith deals honestly and emphatically with the range of emotions,\" wrote Cynthia Westway in ''[[The Atlanta Journal]]'', \"the story is not, however, an elegy; but a celebration of the continuity of the life-death cycle.\"<ref name=\"Atlanta Journal\">{{cite news|last=Westway|first=Cynthia|title=How a Child Responds to Facts of Death|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal|date=August 5, 1973}}</ref>  In the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'', David Rees wrote, \"It will be difficult to find a children's book this autumn by a new author as good as [[Doris Buchanan Smith|Doris Buchanan Smith's]] ''A Taste of Blackberries'' . . . Smith's success lies in knowing how to handle the theme with exactly the right balance of sensitivity, humour and open emotion.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees|first=David|title=The most difficult problem|newspaper=Times Literary Supplement|date=September 19, 1975}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nAs told from the point of view of the unnamed [[narrator]], the story begins as he and his best friend Jamie go blackberry picking. We follow the boys as they take part in a series of exploits - some told in current narrative time, some revealed in poignant flashbacks - allowing the reader to witness their world and shared experience. When one of the boys tragically dies as a result of an [[Anaphylaxis|allergic reaction]] to bee stings, the narrator struggles to cope with denial, grief, guilt, and loneliness, before coming to terms with the loss.  The story is set in a suburb of [[Washington, D.C.]], the author's birthplace.\n\n==Characters==\n*Jamie is a \"show-off and a clown\". While he can be exasperating, his adventurous and resourceful nature earns the admiration of his best friend.\n*The narrator, Jamie's appreciative audience and partner in fun, enjoys their friendship, even if, at times, Jamie can go too far.\n*Heather, with red-gold hair, is the closest friend of both Jamie and the narrator.\n*Jamie's mother cares for a family of three, including Jamie, four-year-old Martha, and an infant son.\n*The narrator's mother and father care for the narrator and a college-age daughter who is away at summer camp as a counselor. They also have a son who is grown and married.\n*Mrs. Houser, Jamie's next door neighbor, is tyrannical when it comes to her perfect lawn. The children in the neighborhood avoid her, and her lawn, if they possibly can.\n*Mrs. Mullins' \"secret garden\" is off limits to most of the children in the neighborhood. The narrator feels privileged to be an exception, mainly because Mrs. Mullins and his mother are friends.\n\n==Literary significance==\n\"In dealing directly with the death of a child's playmate, it broke a taboo of twentieth-century American children's fiction,\" wrote Hugh T. Keenan, in the St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&disableHighlighting=false&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1663000396&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=3ce48fd1879e2c4e7ba70c5f5862ea9a|work=St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers|publisher=Gale Biography In Contex|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>  British author, lecturer and reviewer [[David Rees (author)|David Rees]] drew parallels between ''Charlotte's Web'' and ''A Taste of Blackberries'' in ''The Marble in the Water: Essays on Contemporary Writers of Fiction for Children and Young Adults'' (1980).  He writes that \"in ''A Taste of Blackberries'' we do have a story for young children in which death - sudden and inexplicable - is the main theme, and it is a book in which the characters are not talking animals.\" \"The chief purpose of the book,\" Rees argues, \"is to write about death in a fashion that young readers can take, and in this [[Doris Buchanan Smith]] succeeds admirably.\"  \"These two authors are saying things that are necessary, and which help children to cope and to grow.\"<ref name=\"Rees 1980 66\u201377\">{{cite book|last=Rees|first=David|title=The Marble in the Water: E. B. White and Doris Buchanan Smith|year=1980|publisher=The Horn Book|isbn=0-87675-281-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/marbleinwater00rees/page/66 66\u201377]|url=https://archive.org/details/marbleinwater00rees/page/66}}</ref>  ''A Taste of Blackberries'' is \"one of the seminal children's books on the subject of death.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Welton|first=Ann|title=Buchanan Smith, Doris Un sabor a moras (A Taste of Blackberries)|journal=School Library Journal|date=December 2002|volume=48|issue=12|pages=p.S60|url=http://find.galegroup.com/gps/infomark.do?&contentSet=IAC-Documents&type=retrieve&tabID=T003&prodId=IPS&docId=A95528664&source=gale&srcprod=BCPM&userGroupName=nypl&version=1.0|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Doris Buchanan Smith|Smith]] won the [[Josette Frank Award]], for \"outstanding literary merit in which children or young people deal in a positive and realistic way with difficulties in their world and grow emotionally and morally,\" The author also won the Georgia Children's Book Award,<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgia Children's Book Award|url= http://gcba.coe.uga.edu/gcba-awards/past-book-award-winners-grades-4-8/|publisher=College of Education at the University of Georgia|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> the Children's Best Book Prize in the [[Netherlands]] ([[List of literary awards|Zilveren Griffel]]), and was named Georgia Author of the Year, all for ''A Taste of Blackberries''. In addition to 19 English language editions, the book has been translated into Dutch, Danish, French, Spanish and Japanese.  ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was nominated for the prestigious [[Newbery Medal]] in 1974, and is an [[American Library Association|ALA Notable Children's Book]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1617001845&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=7481e5a51f310a721b285ed3c6bd1627|work=Major Authors and Illustrators for Children and Young Adults|publisher=Gale Biography In Context|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"It blazed the way for the many other grief books that quickly followed, but few have approached the place of honor this one holds,\" wrote [[Jim Trelease]] in ''[[Jim Trelease|The Read-Aloud Handbook]]'' ([[Penguin Books]], 2006).<ref>{{cite book|last=Trelease|first=Jim|title=The Read-Aloud Handbook|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Group (USA) Incorporated|location=New York|isbn=978-0-14-303739-2|pages=236}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Reflist|group=Bibliography}}\n{{Reflist|group=Biography}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://hmfa.libs.uga.edu/hmfa/view?docId=ead/ms2035-ead.xml Doris Buchanan Smith Papers University of Georgia - Hargrett Rare Book and Manuscript Library]\n* [http://special.lib.umn.edu/findaid/xml/CLRC-1841.xml Doris Buchanan Smith Papers University of Minnesota]\n* [http://www.georgiacenterforthebook.org/Georgia-Literary-Map/Georgia-Author-Detail.php?record_id=180 Georgia Center for the Book honors Doris Buchanan Smith]\n* [http://www.harpercollinschildrens.com/books/Taste-Blackberries/?isbn13=9780064402385&tctid=100 HarperCollins' A Taste of Blackberries current edition]\n* [http://bankstreet.edu/center-childrens-literature/childrens-book-committee/awards/ Josette Frank Award]\n* [http://www2.scholastic.com/browse/book.jsp?id=1273 Scholastic Inc. A Taste of Blackberries]\n* [[:nl:Zilveren Griffel|Zilveren Griffel Dutch language article showing Smith's 1977 win]]\n* [http://www.librarything.com/bookaward/Zilveren+Griffel Zilveren Griffel Library Thing page]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taste of Blackberries}}\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:1973 American novels]]\n[[Category:American children's novels]]\n[[Category:Children's books about friendship]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Thomas Y. Crowell Co. books]]\n[[Category:1973 children's books]]\n[[Category:Novels about friendship]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book \n| name     = A Taste of Blackberries\n| title_orig  = \n| image     = File:A Taste of Blackberries library binding.jpg\n| caption = First edition\n| author    = [[Doris Buchanan Smith]]\n| illustrator  = Charles Robinson\n| cover_artist = \n| country    = United States\n| language   = English\n| series    = \n| genre     = [[Children's fiction|Children's novel]] \n| publisher   = [[Thomas Y. Crowell Co.]] (now [[HarperCollins]])\n| release_date = May 1973\n| media_type  = Print\n| pages     = 85 (paperback)\n| awards       = [[ALA Notable Children's Book]], Georgia Children's Author of the Year, Georgia Children's Book Award, Georgia Author of the Year, [[Josette Frank Award]], [[List of literary awards|Zilveren Griffel]]\n| isbn     = 9780064402385\n| congress   = \n| oclc     = \n| preceded_by  = \n| followed_by  = \n}}\n'''''A Taste of Blackberries''''' ([[HarperCollins]], 1973) is an award-winning children's book by [[Doris Buchanan Smith]] (June 1, 1934 - August 8, 2002).<ref>{{cite news|last=Derrick|first=Henry|title=Obituaries: Hayesville, NC: Doris Buchanan Smith, 68, Wrote for Adolescents|pages=P.C6|url=http://find.galegroup.com/gps/infomark.do?&contentSet=IAC-Documents&type=retrieve&tabID=T004&prodId=IPS&docId=CJ121436858&source=gale&srcprod=ITOF&userGroupName=nypl&version=1.0|accessdate=19 April 2011|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=14 August 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&disableHighlighting=false&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1663000396&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=3ce48fd1879e2c4e7ba70c5f5862ea9a|work=St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers|publisher=Gale Biography In Context|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Background and reception==\nWhen [[Doris Buchanan Smith|Doris Smith]] set out to find a publisher for ''A Taste of Blackberries'' what she found instead was rejection.  Editors believed her story was better suited to adults than to children.  In the end however the main theme is what set it apart from other books for children and earned critical acclaim.<ref>{{cite news|last=Scherer|first=Sally|title=Author of Children\u2019s Books Found Success by Breaking Rules|newspaper=The Macon Telegraph|date=18 April 1996}}</ref>  If death had at one time been a common theme in books for children, think ''[[Oliver Twist]]'', it had long since become taboo.  In 1952, [[E. B. White]] reintroduced the theme to young readers in his classic ''[[Charlotte's Web]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Lois Rauch Gibson|author2=Laura M. Zaidman|title=Death in Children's Literature: Taboo or Not Taboo?|journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly|date=Winter 1991|volume=16| issue = 4|pages=232\u2013234|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/childrens_literature_association_quarterly/summary/v016/16.4.gibson.html|accessdate=30 August 2012|doi=10.1353/chq.0.0855}}</ref>\n\nFor many years ''[[Charlotte's Web]]'' was the accepted template for addressing mortality in children's books.  Then Smith's story appeared, a story in which animals do not stand-in for humans.  In the 1970s, [[literary realism]] had taken hold, and Smith was at the vanguard of the movement,<ref>{{cite news|last=Habich|first=John|title=She tells kids the bitter and the sweet|newspaper=Tallahassee Democrat|date=December 1980}}</ref> acquainting young readers with \"the darker, harsher side of life.\"  According to author and blogger Pauline Dewan; \"Many writers believe that authors do not help children by sheltering them from the problems of the real world.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Dewan|first=Pauline|title=Children\u2019s Literary Classics: The Realistic Genre|url=http://childliterature.net/childlit/realistic/index.html|accessdate=29 October 2012}}</ref>  Indeed, according to the author, many young readers told her \"they liked it because it was sad.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Jingle|title=A Realist in Children's Books|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal|date=December 10, 1978}}</ref>  Interviewed for the ''[[Dictionary of Literary Biography]]'', Smith recalled that ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was supposed to have been an adventure, but when an unexpected idea occurred to her Smith put the manuscript in a drawer and forget about it.  Only later did she resume by focusing on the differences in the way that children and adults respond to mortality, while writing from the point of view of the child.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Keenan|first=Hugh T.|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|journal=Dictionary of Literary Biography|year=1981|volume=52|page=353}}</ref>\n\nRejected by as many as three publishers, ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was ultimately accepted by [[Thomas Y. Crowell Co.]], now [[HarperCollins]], and released to wide acclaim in May 1973.  \"Smith deals honestly and emphatically with the range of emotions,\" wrote Cynthia Westway in ''[[The Atlanta Journal]]'', \"the story is not, however, an elegy; but a celebration of the continuity of the life-death cycle.\"<ref name=\"Atlanta Journal\">{{cite news|last=Westway|first=Cynthia|title=How a Child Responds to Facts of Death|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal|date=August 5, 1973}}</ref>  In the ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'', David Rees wrote, \"It will be difficult to find a children's book this autumn by a new author as good as [[Doris Buchanan Smith|Doris Buchanan Smith's]] ''A Taste of Blackberries'' . . . Smith's success lies in knowing how to handle the theme with exactly the right balance of sensitivity, humour and open emotion.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rees|first=David|title=The most difficult problem|newspaper=Times Literary Supplement|date=September 19, 1975}}</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nAs told from the point of view of the unnamed [[narrator]], the story begins as he and his best friend Jamie go blackberry picking. We follow the boys as they take part in a series of exploits - some told in current narrative time, some revealed in poignant flashbacks - allowing the reader to witness their world and shared experience. When one of the boys tragically dies as a result of an [[Anaphylaxis|allergic reaction]] to bee stings, the narrator struggles to cope with denial, grief, guilt, and loneliness, before coming to terms with the loss.  The story is set in a suburb of [[Washington, D.C.]], the author's birthplace.\n\n==Characters==\n*Jamie is a \"show-off and a clown\". While he can be exasperating, his adventurous and resourceful nature earns the admiration of his best friend.\n*The narrator, Jamie's appreciative audience and partner in fun, enjoys their friendship, even if, at times, Jamie can go too far.\n*Heather, with red-gold hair, is the closest friend of both Jamie and the narrator.\n*Jamie's mother cares for a family of three, including Jamie, four-year-old Martha, and an infant son.\n*The narrator's mother and father care for the narrator and a college-age daughter who is away at summer camp as a counselor. They also have a son who is grown and married.\n*Mrs. Houser, Jamie's next door neighbor, is tyrannical when it comes to her perfect lawn. The children in the neighborhood avoid her, and her lawn, if they possibly can.\n*Mrs. Mullins' \"secret garden\" is off limits to most of the children in the neighborhood. The narrator feels privileged to be an exception, mainly because Mrs. Mullins and his mother are friends.\n\n==Literary significance==\n\"In dealing directly with the death of a child's playmate, it broke a taboo of twentieth-century American children's fiction,\" wrote Hugh T. Keenan, in the St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&disableHighlighting=false&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1663000396&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=3ce48fd1879e2c4e7ba70c5f5862ea9a|work=St. James Guide to Young Adult Writers|publisher=Gale Biography In Contex|accessdate=29 April 2011}}</ref>  British author, lecturer and reviewer [[David Rees (author)|David Rees]] drew parallels between ''Charlotte's Web'' and ''A Taste of Blackberries'' in ''The Marble in the Water: Essays on Contemporary Writers of Fiction for Children and Young Adults'' (1980).  He writes that \"in ''A Taste of Blackberries'' we do have a story for young children in which death - sudden and inexplicable - is the main theme, and it is a book in which the characters are not talking animals.\" \"The chief purpose of the book,\" Rees argues, \"is to write about death in a fashion that young readers can take, and in this [[Doris Buchanan Smith]] succeeds admirably.\"  \"These two authors are saying things that are necessary, and which help children to cope and to grow.\"<ref name=\"Rees 1980 66\u201377\">{{cite book|last=Rees|first=David|title=The Marble in the Water: E. B. White and Doris Buchanan Smith|year=1980|publisher=The Horn Book|isbn=0-87675-281-4|pages=[https://archive.org/details/marbleinwater00rees/page/66 66\u201377]|url=https://archive.org/details/marbleinwater00rees/page/66}}</ref>  ''A Taste of Blackberries'' is \"one of the seminal children's books on the subject of death.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Welton|first=Ann|title=Buchanan Smith, Doris Un sabor a moras (A Taste of Blackberries)|journal=School Library Journal|date=December 2002|volume=48|issue=12|pages=p.S60|url=http://find.galegroup.com/gps/infomark.do?&contentSet=IAC-Documents&type=retrieve&tabID=T003&prodId=IPS&docId=A95528664&source=gale&srcprod=BCPM&userGroupName=nypl&version=1.0|accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[Doris Buchanan Smith|Smith]] won the [[Josette Frank Award]], for \"outstanding literary merit in which children or young people deal in a positive and realistic way with difficulties in their world and grow emotionally and morally,\" The author also won the Georgia Children's Book Award,<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgia Children's Book Award|url= http://gcba.coe.uga.edu/gcba-awards/past-book-award-winners-grades-4-8/|publisher=College of Education at the University of Georgia|accessdate=11 March 2014}}</ref> the Children's Best Book Prize in the [[Netherlands]] ([[List of literary awards|Zilveren Griffel]]), and was named Georgia Author of the Year, all for ''A Taste of Blackberries''. In addition to 19 English language editions, the book has been translated into Dutch, Danish, French, Spanish and Japanese.  ''A Taste of Blackberries'' was nominated for the prestigious [[Newbery Medal]] in 1974, and is an [[American Library Association|ALA Notable Children's Book]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Doris Buchanan Smith|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?displayGroupName=Reference&prodId=BIC1&action=e&windowstate=normal&catId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1617001845&mode=view&userGroupName=nypl&jsid=7481e5a51f310a721b285ed3c6bd1627|work=Major Authors and Illustrators for Children and Young Adults|publisher=Gale Biography In Context|accessdate=24 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n\"It blazed the way for the many other grief books that quickly followed, but few have approached the place of honor this one holds,\" wrote [[Jim Trelease]] in ''[[Jim Trelease|The Read-Aloud Handbook]]'' ([[Penguin Books]], 2006).<ref>{{cite book|last=Trelease|first=Jim|title=The Read-Aloud Handbook|year=2006|publisher=Penguin Group (USA) Incorporated|location=New York|isbn=978-0-14-303739-2|pages=236}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Reflist|group=Bibliography}}\n{{Reflist|group=Biography}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://hmfa.libs.uga.edu/hmfa/view?docId=ead/ms2035-ead.xml Doris Buchanan Smith Papers University of Georgia - Hargrett Rare Book and Manuscript Library]\n* [http://special.lib.umn.edu/findaid/xml/CLRC-1841.xml Doris Buchanan Smith Papers University of Minnesota]\n* [http://www.georgiacenterforthebook.org/Georgia-Literary-Map/Georgia-Author-Detail.php?record_id=180 Georgia Center for the Book honors Doris Buchanan Smith]\n* [http://www.harpercollinschildrens.com/books/Taste-Blackberries/?isbn13=9780064402385&tctid=100 HarperCollins' A Taste of Blackberries current edition]\n* [http://bankstreet.edu/center-childrens-literature/childrens-book-committee/awards/ Josette Frank Award]\n* [http://www2.scholastic.com/browse/book.jsp?id=1273 Scholastic Inc. A Taste of Blackberries]\n* [[:nl:Zilveren Griffel|Zilveren Griffel Dutch language article showing Smith's 1977 win]]\n* [http://www.librarything.com/bookaward/Zilveren+Griffel Zilveren Griffe